values:
I leave at 3:00 for Milwaukee.
Our plane leaves at 11 tommorrow.
Peru, woo!
Be back on the 3rd.

For lack of more pressing things to do, I'll babble for a bit.
The carpet cleaner is here right now, I'm tired of hearing the drone of the damn cleaning machine! I'm confined to the living room, as all the carpeted rooms in the house are wet. I haven't done much of anything today, except read and cook a bit. I woke up, made some waffles (that turned out to be basically cookies made in a waffle maker) vacuumed the whole house for the carpet cleaner, read, made some damn good egg salad, and that's about it. Oh, and Teresa called me in her usual awkward manner and stammered about how she was wondering if I had written the article she had asked for yet. Of course I hadn't, she gave it to me about two days ago, but I BS-ed that and told her I'd have it sent in an hour. Apparently she liked it, according to her reply of exclamations.
I've been reading a lot lately. I finished The Elegant Universe, which was the best non-fiction book I've read in a while. I've been on a real non-fiction spin lately, right now I'm reading One Size Fits Few, by Susan Ohanian. It's completely random, but I figured it might give me a better sense of my mom's education jargon. So far, it has-to a point. It mostly talks about California and the school administrators there who are apparently all a bunch of morons and ass holes. The author actually makes what I thought would be a mind numbing subject somewhat humorous. 

"Male baboons exchange greetings by yanking on each other's penis. I don't know how Fortune 500 CEOs, media pundits, and politicians greet each other, but I do know that only one percent of their DNA differs from that of baboons and that ninety-nine percent of what they say about public education is hooey. And worse. And if one hundred baboons sat in a computer lab, they'd produce Moby Dick sooner that one hundered CEOs would tell the truth about the relationship of their advocacy of one-size-fits-all educational standards to upsizing/outsizing their own salary packages, the sideswiping of middle- and working-class America, and the subsidy of state-of-the-scam sports stadiums with their corporate luxury suites, and the push for tax-supported vouchers to private education."

I only have about 25 pages left of that book, and my reading list for this summer keeps growing. I recently raided my mom's bookshelf and realized that she actually has very good taste in books. I took a few to read, and there are about 10 more that I will come back for. So far, my reading list for the recent future includes finishing My Ishmael, and reading: Radical Reflections by Mem Fox, The Golden Ratio by Mario Livio, and Jihad vs. McWorld: Terrorism's Challenge to Democracy by Benjamin R. Barber. 
I really need some new music, my cd collection in my car is growing boring and my ipod converter for the car doesn't work well. I have a gift certificate to Barnes and Noble from my birthday, I think I'll probably go soon and spend it. I want to get The Only Thing I Ever Wanted album by Psapp, and Fidelity by Regina Spekktor. I also want to get a book on the Manu in Peru, I'd like to do some reading on where we are going before we leave. 
Summer has been really great so far, a lack of urgent things to do is a luxury I lost for a while.

I'm in Florida, having a pretty good time. I plan on doing nothing but reading while lying in the sun on the beach, swimming, and taking long walks on the beach while I am here. Actually-that's all I ever do here. Except for the ocassional shopping trip. The boys are hilarious as usual, and Alex is pretty funny too. Our meal last night was so funny, there's something really nice about sitting at the kids table. At our family reunion the boys made nicknames for everyone, they like using them a lot now. Madi is fatty madi, Harry is Scary Fairy Harry, and I am whorin' lauren, or borin' lauren? It's funny because they don't know what a whore is. Alex and Henry don't have nicknames. I'm reading freakanomics, it is very good. Goodnight.

Gah life is so confusing!!!!
People are so confusing?!?!?!

I feel like I have so many good memories that my mind just can't hold them all. I'm waiting for myself to just start forgeting things. I don't like the idea. I miss a lot of people, and more so, memories I have with them.
I'm really scared for monday. It probably(I hope) isn't a big deal, but if it is....wow. I'm just nervous.

I hate this.
I wish I could describe what "this" was.

blah.
school sucks. I'm tired of it already. Notre Dame sucks.

School makes me want to puke.
ugh.

Am I the only person who doubts pretty much anything and everyone?

That sounds like I'm a pretty big pessimist. But that's how it seems lately.

I haven't updated in forever. I haven't felt the need to. In the summer life is pretty laid back and not too stressful, and as I'm not the type to run through my daily activities I haven't written much. China was great, and I'm leaving for Vermont in about...4 hours. I have a lot on my mind, good and bad. I feel like this school year is going to bring a lot of change, I'm not sure I'm ready for it. I don't like the school year. Especially the winter. I'm always depressed in the winter, and super stressed.

Instead of posting all my pictures, I'm just posting the link to my facebook pictures.

http://hs.facebook.com/photos.php?id=1606380177&l=55780

I'm home! 
It was AMAZING.
I will most likely post pictures later.

I am hella nervous.
I doubt I am going to be able to sleep tonight.
I hope I remember everything.
And that the dinky little travel clock alarm actually wakes me up.
Adios Chicos y Chicas!

I thought I had something to say.
I got nothing.

I love how music can change your mood in a moment. I wonder what my life would be like with out music. I mean, considering that I pretty much constantly have music playing, except for when I'm at school. I go to shows most weekends, and I've met a ton of my friends through shows. I love the way music can make you feel. Like, it can change your mood from one extreme to the other, even when nothing really has changed. I love how you can listen to a song you loved years ago and it brings back tons of memories. At least that's what it does for me.

I'm really going to miss writing while I'm in China. I am taking a travel journal though. My parents both do whenever they travel. And it's cool, they have an easy way to remember now what they did each day in Peru, Africa, India, and Australia. (Yes, my parents travel A LOT) I'm not sure how much time I will have to write though, on this trip. I think we are going to be running all day, and then coming back for only a short time before they have "lights out." Thats dumb that they have a time when you have to have lights out. I mean, if I turn the lights off and just sit when I'm not tired, it's almost a guarantee that I won't be able to sleep. For some reason, I just have to wait till I'm almost asleep and then shut off my light.

I'm really going to miss everyone around here too, friends and my parents. Not seeing my parents for two weeks won't be a big deal, though. For most people it might seem like it, but they are always traveling for long periods of time. When I was in like 5th grade they went to Hawaii for two weeks, 8th grade Peru for two weeks, 9th grade Africa for almost three weeks, then this year India for a little over two weeks, and my dad also went to Australia for three weeks. So I'm used to them being away. But it will be weird being away from everyone(including friends) for this long. I mean, it's only two weeks, but I don't know anyone who is going. It's not like I'll have anyone I can rely on except myself. I'm sure I'll meet people, but it will be really hard to fly a 14 hour flight and not know anyone on it. I'm really happy we are flying through Tokyo now though, Even if I just get to see Tokyo through the window, it will still be cool. I got good seats on the plane, an aisle from San Fransisco to Tokyo, and window from tokyo to Beijing. So I can sleep for the boring ride, and look out the window when there is something to see. I'm almost done packing, and things are looking good that I will have enough space to pack what I want. They changed the limit once again so I can now only bring 40 lbs. for my main suitcase, and a 10 lb. carry on. They said we can't do laundry there, so it should be interesting. I'm going to have to do some laundry in the sink in the hotel, my mom gave me this soap stuff for handwashing. I don't want to wear the same thing two time without washing it, especially since it is going to be super hot and sweaty there.

If anyone wants a postcard- be sure to give me your address before I leave. I will hopefully be able to send mail while I'm there.
Sincerely, 
Lauren
These are some old family photos I found.
I got exactly what I needed.

I leave for China in 9 days. I just recently realized that it is not infact two and a half weeks untill I leave, but just over one week. I am most definately not ready at all for the trip. I need shoes and a bag to bring-apparently the bag I was going to bring as a purse isn't good enough because it doesn't have a zipper. 
I am super nervous for the plane ride. If I actually suceed at getting to San Fransico by myself, which will be interesting as I'm flying through Chicago which has an enormous aiprport, I have to find the baggage claim there(in SF) and find the people who are taking me to University of California-San Fran. Then I go and check in there and start meeting people. We stay at the University one night before we leave for Shanghai. The plane ride is 14 HOURS. The longest I've ever been on was to Hawaii which was only about 8 hours. I hope I can get an asle seat on the plane, otherwise I'm going to die. My legs are always skwished in all the seats, but at least an asle seat is a little better.
This is the itinerary of what I will be doing: http://lead-america.org/conferences/wylc/china_itinerary.html
This summer is going so so soooo fast. After I get home from China, there will be just one more month untill school begins. And a week of that I will be spending in Vermont for my Craftsbury camp. The camp should be really fun. We have 14 on the water sessions over the course of 5 days. The camp is on this great lake with smooth water. I'm excited to get better at sculling. 
Last night I went to Ihop and Barnes and Noble with Emily, Jaci and Sean. It was really random. We showed up at ihop, realized none of us had money to spend, and then left to go to Barnes and Noble. We went there and Emily saw a car that looked a lot like hers-but she was driving the van that night. And it turned out it was her sister, Stephanie. We went in and Emily called her. We got coffee and a brownie there, and Stephanie and her friends were on their way to leave. Matt came back in and was like "The van isn't starting" So we all went outside to see what was the problem. The engine wasn't even turning over, and we couldn't figure out what was wrong. Steph called their parents and her dad got all mad thinking that she did something to mess the car up. Long story short I completely missed my curfew. But whatever, my mom didn't really care-she was pretty much passed out.
Today I am hanging out with Abby and Aubrey. It seems like we don't hang out nearly as much anymore. It kind of sucks. Later tonight I'm going over to Brittany's house for a party. It should be fun. 
I have a bunch of bugbites, eww. They are almost all from the fireworks at Elkhart. We attempted to watch them, but after the first few there was an accident and they all blew up in this giant cloud of black smoke. The boat they were launched off of was spinning around like crazy! The fireworks injured 6 people, and one flew into the crowd at a Rehersal Dinner at Seibkins. The bride to be got sever burns all over her hands and stomach. She was supposed to get married the next day, but now she's in the hosital. That's horrible.

I got back from Elkhart today. It was ok. Last year was a lot more fun though. I got to see my whole family though, including my grandma and grandpa, which is nice. My grandma is sweet. And my grandpa is really funny. They did the whole like "proud grand parents" thing about me going to China. My trip is in only a week and a half, btw. Holy shit thats soon. I just looked at my computer calender. I thought it was 2 and a half weeks. I am not ready at all. My grandpa also wanted me to help him with sudoku. Dammit there's no food in the house except brownies and deviled eggs.

Tonight I went to the fireworks. It was pretty fun.

I was supposed to go to Brianne's cabin tommorow. I told her I couldn't. I guess I could have, but we leave Thursday or Friday for Elkhart for a week, and then on the 15th I leave for China, and I NEED to start getting ready for it. I need to start shopping for clothes that will be comfortable to wear in 90 degree China weather, that are also addherent to the dress code for the trip. My mom is so tired of shopping for China the other day she was just like "Who cares if you ever wear them again? I don't really give a damn anymore, we'll donate them after you get back."

We are leaving for Elkhart Thursday or Friday, I'm not sure how that will go. It's fun for the first few days...but then it generally gets old hanging out with Maggie and whoever she brings along. Last year I swear we went to Wal-Mart or "Went to Wal-Mart" at LEAST 3 times a day, no exageration. And then the'd drive like maniacs-one time they decided to see just how fast Maggies car could go-she didn't even have her license yet, and she went 150mph! It was scary. Madi and I were in the back seat, and I think we both thought we were gonna die or something.

I got back last night from Madison. I was there for the Badger State Regatta. It was really fun-Lars, Linda Gruber, Anne, Cora and I drove down Friday and met Maggie to stay at Linda Maier's house for the night. On the way, Lars car overheated and we had to stop. We stopped at what we thought was a gas station (The entrance and sign were facing away from the highway) It turned out to be a bar. The bar was called "Kinda Country" and it was pretty weird. As we got out of the car these "biker boys" rolled in on their Harleys. The bar had this giant "Bikers welcome!" sign in the front. We popped the hood to Lars car, and the coolant was bubbling through the overflow. We used the contents of my water bottle as temporary coolant, and went inside to wait for the engine to cool. We walked in, and only one of us was actually 21 (Cora) but they didn't check our I.D's. We had nothing better to do so we played darts.....and found out just how amazing I am at darts(not very) We finally got back on the road, and got to Madison ok. There were a lot of earwigs on the floor at Lindas, but Maggie and I stole the beds so it was ok. The races went pretty well. I was in the Novice 4, the open womens 4, and the open womens 8 and mixed 8. I stroked all of them, so it sort of sucked. We got 2nd in our Novice 4, and the mixed 8 took 3rd, which was really good, especially since Allison from Appelton rowed with us for Katie because she was sick. Steve coxed our womens 8, or "Stephanie" as we called him. It was really funny, he wore a tiara for the whole race. At the start line everyone was laughing, he looked ridiculous. 

That's all JAMIE.

Blah blah blah show tonight-Red Letter Memories and a bunch of other bands at Wheels in Motion. Oh shit...that's out in Howard isn't it. Ughhh.....that will take way to much gas. Last night Jennifer slept over. We went to Sam's house. He was schwasted. Oh damn it was really funny. Like...seeing your cousins like that is pretty ridiculous. And one of his friends (a girl) started doing a strip dance...but couldn't because she kept falling over. And....this one crazy guy went streaking. Yeah. It was pretty interesting.

Today the car died. I was turning into my neighborhood from the highway and the acceleration on the gas, the power steering, and most of the breaking power went out. It sucked, and I almost went into the ditch. This is going to suck. My mom can't drive, and I doubt they will give me a rental car to drive while my moms car is getting fixed. This week is getting even more fun as it goes along...
I

Today I woke up and went to the doctor to get yet another shot to go to China. I had to get some meningoninja-something one so I don't get some weird disease. I came home to these Irrigation system people puting in these hoses for the new irrigation system? I don't really know how it works. But anyways, they proceeded to in 2 hours time cut through our internet and cable tv cables, and cut through a gas line. Untill about an hour ago niether the T.V. or Internet worked. I also spent 2 hours of the afternoon outside while we waited for the public service people to come out and fix the gas line. The whole house smelled like rotten eggs from the natural gas, and it gives you a terrible headache.
I'm really happy. I don't have a specific reason, but that doesn't matter to me. Yesterday I looked out my window and saw this: Cute little baby racoon.
